Uniting all data in one datafram df:

uniting_data <- function(path, extension = "csv"){
  pattern <- paste0("*.", extension)
  myfiles <-  paste0(path, list.files(path, pattern=pattern, all.files=FALSE,
           full.names=FALSE))
  rbindlist(lapply(myfiles, function(x){read.csv(x, stringsAsFactors = F, sep=',')}))
}
path <- "Data/"

df <- uniting_data(path)

As we can see, our data is not normally distributed (specifically days spent in hospital for females receiving drug type 2) and the number of observations is not really that big. It follows that t-test cannot be used, but instead Mann-Whitney U-test:

#Mann-Whitney U test
wlic <- wilcox.test(wdf_plac$days_in_hospital, wdf_2$days_in_hospital)
wlic <- tidy(wlic)
names(wlic) <- c("Statistic", "P Value", "Method", "Alternative Hypothesis")
wlic
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   Statistic `P Value` Method                       `Alternative Hypothesis`
##       <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>                        <chr>                   
## 1       497  0.000221 Wilcoxon rank sum exact test two.sided

Description as in article: Days spent in hospital of females receiving place and drug of type 2 were compared. As the sample size was quite small and the days spent in hospital, Mann-Whitney test was run with test statistic equal to 497 and p-Value of 2.2051037^{-4}. It can be concluded, that the days spent in hospital significantly defer from each other. 6. Is there a difference in the number of days spent in the hospital between taking a drug and placebo?

There doesn’t really seem to be much difference, though let’s check with one-way anova. Null hypothesis - the means of th different groups are the same. Alternative hypothesis - at least one sample mean is not equal to others. Conditions:

  1. Independent and random observations from factors
  2. Data for each factor normally distributed
  3. They have common variance

Checking for normal distribution:

ggplot(df, aes(days_in_hospital, fill = drug_type))+
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)+
  facet_grid(. ~ drug_type)

shapiro.test(df[drug_type=="Placebo", ]$days_in_hospital) #normally distributed
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df[drug_type == "Placebo", ]$days_in_hospital
## W = 0.96695, p-value = 0.1734
shapiro.test(df[drug_type=="Old_type", ]$days_in_hospital) #normally distributed
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df[drug_type == "Old_type", ]$days_in_hospital
## W = 0.99036, p-value = 0.9541
shapiro.test(df[drug_type=="New_type_1", ]$days_in_hospital) #not normally distributed :(
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df[drug_type == "New_type_1", ]$days_in_hospital
## W = 0.91886, p-value = 0.002146
shapiro.test(df[drug_type=="New_type_2", ]$days_in_hospital) #normally distributed
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df[drug_type == "New_type_2", ]$days_in_hospital
## W = 0.96725, p-value = 0.1785

Based on the Shapiro-Wilk test data for each factor is normally distributed, except for new drug of type 1. However, p value is 0.0021455, and not that low, and based on the density distribution - it is not bimodal, so it still okay to use the Anova test.

Checking for common variance with Levene’s test for homogeneity of variance:

lev <- leveneTest(days_in_hospital ~ drug_type, df)
## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.
lev$`Pr(>F)`[1]
## [1] 8.030055e-06

Based on the Levene’s test (p_value = 8.0300548^{-6}), we are not allowed to do the ANOVA-test, because there is statistically different variance across groups.

After visualizing the variances, we can use the F-test of ANOVA:

res.aov <- aov(days_in_hospital ~ drug_type, data = df)
summary(res.aov)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## drug_type     3     89   29.66   1.701  0.168
## Residuals   196   3417   17.43
plot(res.aov, 1)

Based on this there is no significant difference between the days spent in the hospital in groups taking different types of drugs.

ANOVA calculation by another function, take linear model:

The days that one stays in the hospital is not affected by the drug type taken (F = 1.7011706, p_value = 0.1681007, df_1 = 3, df_2 = 196). The result might be skewed, as some of the conditions required in order to perform the ANOVA test were not fulfilled. The ANOVA test is robust and not be affected as much, however, further statistical analysis could be necessary.
